<p class=MsoBodyText><span style='font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>



<p class=MsoBodyText><span style='font-size:10.0pt'>If you want to experiment

with different device ROM</span><!--[if supportFields]><span style='font-size:

10.0pt'><span style='mso-element:field-begin'></span></span><![endif]--><!--[if supportFields]><span

style='font-size:10.0pt'><span style='mso-element:field-end'></span></span><![endif]--><span

style='font-size:10.0pt'>'s, you will need to either download your own device's

ROM (using a serial cable and the &quot;ROM Transfer&quot; app that comes with

POSE) or get ROM's from Palm, Inc. (or your device's manufacturer). From Palm,

Inc.'s web site at <a href="http://www.palmos.com/dev/tools/emulator/">www.palmos.com/dev/tools/emulator/</a>:<o:p></o:p></span></p>



<p class=MsoBodyText><span style='font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>



<p class=SBBody style='margin-top:0in;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:0in;

margin-left:.5in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'><span

style='font-size:9.0pt'><span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> </span>&quot;For legal

reasons, you must sign an agreement with Palm Inc. to download ROM images. To

obtain the agreement, you must be a member of the Palm OS Developer Program.

After joining that program, we recommend that you also join the Developer

Seeding Program, which requires that you return a signed agreement to us. This

allows you to access pre-release ROM images and other valuable tools. If you

are based in the </span><st1:country-region><st1:place><span style='font-size:

  9.0pt'>USA</span></st1:place></st1:country-region><span style='font-size:

9.0pt'>, you may also obtain images using a &quot;<span class=SpellE>clickwrap</span>&quot;

agreement that does not require a signed agreement.&quot;<span

style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>



<p class=MsoBodyText><span style='font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>



<p class=MsoBodyText><span style='font-size:10.0pt'>I couldn't have said it any

better.<o:p></o:p></span></p>



<h3><a name="_Toc5216083"></a><a name="_Toc5215820"></a><a name="_Toc3993354"><span

style='mso-bookmark:_Toc5215820'><span style='mso-bookmark:_Toc5216083'><span

style='font-size:10.0pt'>Installing POSE</span></span></span></a><!--[if supportFields]><span

style='font-size:10.0pt'><span style='mso-element:field-begin'></span></span><![endif]--><!--[if supportFields]><span

style='font-size:10.0pt'><span style='mso-element:field-end'></span></span><![endif]--><span

style='font-size:10.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></h3>



<p class=MsoBodyText><span style='font-size:10.0pt'>POSE</span><!--[if supportFields]><span

style='font-size:10.0pt'><span style='mso-element:field-begin'></span></span><![endif]--><!--[if supportFields]><span

style='font-size:10.0pt'><span style='mso-element:field-end'></span></span><![endif]--><span

style='font-size:10.0pt'> is normally installed with the NSBasic for Palm

installation, and should exist in your NSBasic Tools directory (by default at

c:\nsbasic\tools).<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>If you are installing

POSE from the zipped archive, extract the emulator files into a new directory

(I'd call it &quot;POSE&quot;, but you can use whatever name you'd like).<span

style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Create a subdirectory named &quot;Skins&quot;

within this directory, and extract the skin files here.<span

style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>This directory MUST be named

&quot;Skins&quot;, and the skin files MUST be in this directory, in order for

POSE to find them.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Note that when you

attempt to extract the skins, they will go to their previously stored directory

names unless you tell your uninstaller (I use WinZip ñ you can get the latest

version at www.winzip.com) to ignore the directory names.<span

style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>If you forget this step, and POSE always

starts with the default &quot;generic&quot; skin, look at the &quot;Skins&quot;

directory, and you'll probably see another directory within it that contains

the skins.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Move the skins to the

&quot;Skins&quot; directory, and everything should work appropriately.<o:p></o:p></span></p>



<p class=MsoBodyText><span style='font-size:10.0pt'>These skins aren't merely

close approximations ñ they have the exact look <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:

normal'>and feel</i> of the real Palm devices, like this PalmIIIc: <o:p></o:p></span></p>



<p class=MsoBodyText><span style='font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>



